1f971.title: Yawning Face
1f971.description:
A yellow face with eyes closed and mouth wide open covered by a hand. Captured mid-yawn, this may represent having insufficient sleep, or to imply boredom with a person or topic.
Not to be confused with 😪 Sleepy Face or 😴 Sleeping Face, which often convey actually being asleep, or 😫 Tired Face which is tired as in "fed up".

1f90d.title: White Heart
1f90d.description:
A white heart emoji to accompany other hearts such as ❤️🧡💛💚💙💜🖤 approved as part of Emoji 12.0 in 2019. A popular request, and coming to major platforms throughout 2019.
A character known as White Heart Suit is sometimes used in its place, but this is not intended to have an emoji appearance.

1f9a7.title: Orangutan
1f9a7.description:
An orangutan, the orange-haired ape with long arms. Depicted facing forward, with a long broad face and sitting with its legs bent. Often shown scratching its head. Skin color varies across platforms, ranging from light to dark.
Google’s orangutan has purplish skin, Twitter's is smiling.

1f9ae.title: Guide Dog
1f9ae.description:
A guide (or Seeing Eye) dog, trained to help lead a person who is blind or visually impaired. Generally depicted as a yellowish-brown Labrador Retriever on all fours facing left, equipped with a harness and handle. Many platforms additionally include a collar.
Not to be confused with 🐕‍🦺 Service Dog, though their popular applications may overlap.
Twitter implements the same dog as its 🐕 Dog. Samsung and Twitter’s guide dogs have green harnesses.

1f415-200d-1f9ba.title: Service Dog
1f415-200d-1f9ba.description:
A service animal displayed with a safety vest and lead. Differs from the guide dog as this animal is intended for detection of seizures or other “hidden disabilities”, according to the proposal from Apple.
The Service Dog emoji is a sequence of the 🐕 Dog and 🦺 Safety Vest emojis.
These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms.

1f9a5.title: Sloth
1f9a5.description: A sloth, the slow-moving, tree-dwelling mammal. Depicted as a light-brown sloth with a wide, whitish, masked face hanging from a tree branch, facing left or right. Generally shown as a three-toed sloth.

1f9a6.title: Otter
1f9a6.description:
An otter, the playful water mammal in the weasel family. Depicted as a light-brown otter on its back, with its forepaws held together and whiskered face to the left, generally with its long tail curled up.
Apple’s otter is in water, holding a stone, as is Microsoft’s.

1f9a8.title: Skunk
1f9a8.description:
A skunk, a bushy-tailed mammal that sprays a foul odor when threatened. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with black hair and its distinctive white stripe running from its head down to a curled-up tail.
Google’s skunk bears a humorously haughty air.

1f9a9.title: Flamingo
1f9a9.description:
A flamingo, a waterbird with pink feathers and long neck and legs. Depicted as a flamingo in full profile facing left, standing on one leg, usually with a long, black beak.
May be used to represent summer fun or as a pink accent color.

1f9aa.title: Oyster
1f9aa.description: An oyster, a mollusk used for food or pearls. Depicted as half of an opened oyster with a pinkish body in a rough, brown-and-white shell, bearing a pearl on many platforms.

1f9c9.title: Mate
1f9c9.description:
Mate is a caffeinated beverage popular in many South American countries. Green in color (from a key ingredient: the dried leaves of yerba mate) and consumed via a metal straw.
This drink is commonly referred to as yerba mate in English, and sometimes spelled maté (to distinguish from a mate, as in friend).

1f9bd.title: Manual Wheelchair
1f9bd.description: A wheelchair without any motor. Distinct from ♿ Wheelchair Symbol which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also Woman in Manual Wheelchair or Man in Manual Wheelchair.

1f9bc.title: Motorized Wheelchair
1f9bc.description: A wheelchair with a motor. Distinct from ♿ Wheelchair Symbol which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also Woman in Motorized Wheelchair or Man in Motorized Wheelchair.

1f6fa.title: Auto Rickshaw
1f6fa.description: An auto rickshaw (often referred to as a tuk tuk) is a motorized version of a cycle rickshaw, used for transport in many regions of the world. Generally has three wheels and various levels of shelter from the outside elements (some open air, some are enclosed).

1f9ba.title: Safety Vest
1f9ba.description: A brightly colored vest generally worn on construction sites or areas requiring high visibility.

1fa72.title: Briefs
1fa72.description: Underwear or swim briefs (aka "Speedos"), in a style most often associated with men.

1fa70.title: Ballet Shoes
1fa70.description: A pointe shoe worn by ballet dancers when performing pointe work.

1f9af.title: Probing Cane
1f9af.description: A probing cane, used by some people who are blind or visually impaired. Differs from a support cane, and is sometimes referred to as a white cane. See also 👩‍🦯 Woman With Probing Cane and 👨‍🦯 Man With Probing Cane.

1fa78.title: Drop of Blood
1fa78.description: A drop of blood shown in red. May be used to signify a blood donation, bleeding, injury or menstruation.

1fa91.title: Chair
1fa91.description:
A chair for sitting at a table, or in a standalone location. Materials may vary, with wood a common choice.
Distinct from the seat emoji, which is generally fixed, as opposed to a chair which can be moved.

1fa92.title: Razor
1fa92.description: A razor which may be displayed as a razor blade or a safety razor.
